column168: Description Of Events

CUSTOMER WAS UNLOADING PRODUCT WHILE DRIVER WAITED IN THE BREAK ROOM. CUSTOMER LEFT THE TANK UNLOADING FOR A FEW MINUTES AND RETURNED TO AN OVERFLOWED TANK.  ATOCHEM ACCEPTED RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE SPILL.

THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT CARLISLE FROM THE DEFENSE DEPOT OF MECHANICSBURG DAMAGED AND LEAKING.  THIS FREIGHT WAS EITHER STRUCK WITH THE BLUNT END OF A FORKLIFT OR DAMAGED BY OTHER FREIGHT.  THE LEAKAGE WAS MINIMAL AND SOAKED INTO THE CARDBOARD OUTER CONTAINER.  NO MATERIAL WAS LOST OUTSIDE OF THE SHRINKWRAPPED PALLET.  THE PALLET WAS DISMANTLED AND THE DAMAGED BOTTLE COMPLETELY CONTAINED.

DRIVER WAS ASCENDING A THREE LANE HILL WITHIN THE CITY LIMITS OF WEIRTON, WV ON 10-2-91 AT 16:30 HOURS WHEN AN EXPANSION PLUG (5PSI MARKING) ON THE TOP SIDE OF THE TRAILER FAILED. AN ESTIMATED 15-20 GALLONS SPLASHED OUT AND WENT ONTO THE HIGHWAY SURFACE. THE VEHICLE STOPPED IMMEDIATELY AND THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED CONTAINMENT WITH HIS SPILL CONTROL KIT.  OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED UPON NOTIFICATION AS DID THE WEIRTON FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR DAMAGES.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: AT 0830 HRS OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING HIS FREIGHT AT MCCLELLEN AFB IN SACRAMENTO CA.  ON 10/03/91.  HE AND THE RECIEVING CLERK NOTICED A SMELL OF ACID.  THEN NOTICED THE SPILL OF APPROX 1 US PINT OF LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  AT THIS TIME THE US AIR FORCE FIRE DEPT. WAS CALL AND ISOLATED THE AREA.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY THE PERSONNEL AT THAT TIME.  THERE APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN A PROBLEM WITH THE SEALING OF THE LID ON THE PLASTIC PAIL.  IN THE FUTURE WHEN SHIPMENTS OF THIS TYPE ARE HANDLED BY CON-WAY.  DRIVERS HAVE BEEN TOLD TO DOUBLE CHECK LIDS FOR TIGHTNESS AND TO MAKE SURE THEY ARE SECURE.  LOCKING DEVICES SHOULD BE PLACED ON CONTAINERS THAT CARRY MATERIAL OF THIS TYPE.  IF A CAP OR LID USED ON MEDICINE BOTTLES WERE INPLACE, RATHER THEN THE STANDARD SCREW CAP.  THE LID WOULD HAVE BEEN UNABLE TO COME LOOSE OR FAIL.

column168: ONE OF TWENTY FOUR 55 GALLON DRUMS HAD VERY MINOR LEAK DUE TO RUBBING INSIDE CONTAINER.  LEAK WAS AT WORN CHIME.  DRUM WAS REPAIRED CONTAINER CLEANED, RELOADED, AND FOREWARDED TO DESTINATION.
SHIPMENT WAS LOADED WITH OTHER FREIGHT ON TOP FROM CAROLINA'S CHICAGO TERMINAL TO THE CARLISLE TERMINAL.  THE FREIGHT ON TOP WAS TOO HEAVY AND CRUSHED THE BOTTOM FREIGHT.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN PRIMARY UNLOAD.  ONE OF FOUR, 4 LT. BOTTLES HAD A LOOSE CAP.  THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

PACKAGE CONTAINED METAL "PAINT CANS" WHICH HAD NO CLIPS.  THE UNDAMAGED PORTION WAS REPACKED, PUTTING CLIPS ON THE CANS TO HOLD LIDS AND WAS SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER. THE DAMAGED BOX, CAN AND PACKING MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.  CANS NEED TO HAVE CLIPS TO HOLD LID DOWN AND KEEP IT FROM POPPING UP.

LID WAS TIGHTENED TO STOP AND MATERIAL FROM LEAKING OUT.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE LIQUID HAD LEAKED OUT, WHICH MADE BOX DAMP.  CANS WERE REMOVED FROM BOX AND BOX WAS LEFT TO DRY IN OPEN VENTILATED AREA.  AFTER BOX WAS DRY CANS WERE REPLACED IN BOX AND BOX WAS RETAPED.  BOX WAS DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE. BIRCH RUN DOCKMAN WORKED TRAILER APPROXIMATELY 10:15 AM.  NOTICED AN ODOR IN THE TRIALER & SPOTTED LEAKING DRUM WHEN HE REMOVED PALLET BEHIND THE DRUMS GOING TO PENDELL PRINTING IN MIDLAND, MICHIGAN.  HE NOTIFIED DISPATCH IMMEDIATELY, A PHOTO WAS TAKEN, AND DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAYED ON ITS SIDE ON A PALLET.  PRODUCT WAS OF A HIGHLY CONGEALING NATURE, SO OUR BEST ESTIMATE IS THAT THERE WERE APPRIXIMATELY 2 GALLONS SPILLED ON TRAILER FLOOR.  I PURPOSELY QUESTIONED OUR BIRCH RUN DOCKMAN TO MAKE SURE THAT HE WAS NOT THE ONE WHO PUNCTURED THE DRUM AS HE REMOVE THE PALLET BEHIND THE DRUMS.  HE CONVINCED ME THAT HE DID NOT, STATING THAT HE KNEW HIS FORKLIFT PRONGS WERE NOT EXTENDED BEYOND PALLET EDGE AND THAT HE WOULD NOT HAVE HAD ANY PROBLEM TELLING ANYONE IF HE HAD BEEN RESPONSIBLE.  IN ADDITION, THE PICTURE ENCLOSED SHOWS THE PUNCTURED AS IT FACED UPON ARRIVAL AT BIRCH RUN.  THERE IS A SLIGHT ANGLE TO THE PUNCTURE THAT SEEMED TO PRECLUDE ITS BEING CAUSED BY HIS REMOVEAL OF FREIGHT BEHIND THE PUNCTURE HAD A SLIGHT ANGLE TOWARDS WALL OF TRAILER.

EMPLOYEE OF CDR TURNED OFF HOSE - THE PUMP WAS STILL GOING. PRESSURE BUILT UP AND BLEW HOSE CONTROL OFF END OF HOSE AND SPRAYED LIQUID ON EMPLOYEE AND GROUND.  (APPROXIMATELY 35 GALLONS OF POLYESTER RESIN) EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN TO PUTNAMD COMMUNITY HOSPITAL WHER HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED BY THE HOSPITAL PERSONNEL TO DETERMINE PROPER MEDICAL TREATMENT.  IN CHECKING THE EQUIPMENT, IT WAS DETERMINED THE CAUSE OF THE PROBLEM WAS A IMPROPERLY COUPLED HOSE.  THE HOSE WAS FOREIGN TO REICHHOLD, TUSCALOOSA FLEEY.  THE HOSE COULD HAVE BEEN STITCHED WHILE SPOTTED AT A WASHRACK, AT A PLANT, BY ANOTHER CARRIER OR NAY NUMBER OF OTHER LOCATIONS.  I AM HAVING THE TRACTORS IN THE TUSCALOOSA FLEET EQUIPPED TO CARRY THEIR OWN HOSES AS OPPOSED TO LEAVING HOSES ON THE TRAILERS.  THE HOSES WILL BE BANDED WIHT IDENTIFICATION AS TO TERMINAL LOCATION AND DATE TESTED.  DRIVERS WHO FAIL TO CHECK FOR IMPROPER EQUIPMENT WILL BE STRICTLY REPRIMANDED.  THE SPILLED MATERAIL ON THE GROUND WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL BY ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES. INC LOCATED AT 9559 SUNBEAM CENTER DRIVE, JACKSONVILLE, FL 32257.

column168: THIS MATTER INVOLVES A LOAD OF CLASS I HAZARDOUS WASTE THAT WAS ACCIDENTALLY UNLOADED AT A NON HAZARDOUS LANDFILL.  LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (FS), INC., REGULARY TRANSPORTS BOTH HAZARDOUS AND NON HAZARDOUS WASTE FROM THE OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL CORPORATION, DEER PARK, TEXAS FACILITY. AS THE GENERATOR, OCCIDENTAL DIRECTS SHIPMENT FROM THEIR FACILITY TO VARIOUS WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITIES. ON OCTOBER 4, 1991 A LAIDLAW DRIVER, TRACTOR AND ROLLOFF TRAILER, WERE DISPATCHED TO OCCIDENTAL'S DEER PARK, TEXAS FACILITY,  UPON ARRIVAL, THE DRIVER PERFORMED ROUTINE ONSITE WORK. THEREAFTER, OCCIDENTAL INSTRUCTED LAIDLAW'S DRIVER TO TRANSPORT A ROLLOFF BIN CONTAINING NONHAZARDOUS WASTE TO THE HAZELWOOD MUNICIPAL LANDFILL. THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN A COPY OF THE "OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL CORPORATION NONHAZARDOUS INDUSTRIAL WASTE DISPOSAL TICKET/BILL OF LADING" WHICH INDICATED THAT BIN NO. 9030-08-0 WAS THE CONTAINER TO BE TRANSPORTED.  THE DRIVER WEIGHTED OUT AT OCCIDENTAL'S SCALES AND PROCEEDED TO THE HAZELWOOD LANDFILL WHERE HE WAS DIRECTED TO UNLOAD BIN AT A SPECIFIC LOCATION. ON OCTOBER 5, 1991, OCCIDENTAL NOTIFIED LAIDLAW THAT IT HAD PICKED UP THE WRONG BIN.  LAIDLAW MISTAKENLY TRANSPORTED BIN NO. 9030-01-0 WHICH CONTAINED 20 CUBIC YARDS OF CLASS I HAZARDOUS WASTE.  LAIDLAW NOTIFIED THE OWNER OF THE LANDFILL THAT IT HAD MISTAKENLY UNLOADED A HAZARDOUS WASTE BIN INTO THEIR NONHAZARDOUS LANDFILL.  THE LANDFILL OWNER MARKED THE AREA WHERE THE BIN WAS UNLOADED WITH STAKES. ON OCTOBER 7, 1991 OCCIDENTAL NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT NO. 91288) AND THE TEXAS WATER COMMISSION.  THE HAZELWOOD FACILITY NOTIFIED THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH, REGION IV.  ON OCTOBER 8, 1991 INTERESTED PARTIES MET TO DEVELOP A PLANT TO CORRECT THE ERROR. REGULATORY GUIDANCE WAS SOUGHT FROM THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH. ON OCTOBER 10, 1991 OCCIDENTAL ADVISED LAIDLAW THAT THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH IN CONSULTATION WITH THE TEXAS WATER COMMISSION, HAD AGREED UPON A PLAN TO REMOVE AN ESTIMATED 180 CUBIC YARDS OF POTENTIALLY CONTAMINATED MATERIAL FROM THE LANDFILL.  THE EXCAVATED MATERIAL WAS TO BE SHIPPED TO A CLASS I HAZARDOUS DISPOSAL FACILITY. LAIDLAW AGREED TO PAY FOR THE COST TO EXCAVATE, TRANSPORT AND DISPOSE OF THE POTENTIALLY CONTAMINATED MATERIAL. EXCAVATION COMMENCED THE MORNING OF OCTOBER 11, 1991 AND WAS COMPLETED BY LATE AFTERNOON. EXCAVATED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN SEVEN (7) TARPED ROLLOFF CONTAINERS. RANDOM SAMPLES WEERE TAKEN FROM THE EXCAVATED AREA BY ROY F. WESTON CONSULTING ENGINEERS TO VERIFY THAT ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE LANDFILL.  REPRESENTATIVES OF THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH OBSERVED ACTIVITIES DURING EXCAVATION. ON OCTOBER 16, 1991 OCCIDENTAL ADVISED LAIDLAW THAT THE ANALYSIS INDICATED NO FURTHER EXCAVATION WOULD BE REQUIRED.  THEY FURTHER ADVISED THAT U.S.P.C.I. HAD AGREED TO ACCEPT THIS MATERIAL AT THEIR CLASS I HAZARDOUS LANDFILL IN LONE MOUNTAIN, OKLAHOMA. LAIDLAW HAS TAKEN THE FOLLOWING ACTIONS TO PREVENT A REOCCURREN

AT APPROXIMATELY 1140 HOURS, FRIDAY, OCTOBER 04, 1991, DOT/FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR J DURBAN DISCOVERED A LOSS OF VAPOR PRODUCT FROM THE TOP VALVE AREA OF TANK CAR SCMX-1033 (METHYL  ETHYL KEYTONE) LOCATED ON #5 SHOP TRACK THE CONRAIL DICKINSON RAIL YARD IN DIAMOND, WV.  THIS TRACK IS LEASED BY THE E.I. DUPONT COMPANY FOR STORAGE OF RAIL CARS.  INSPECTOR DURBAN DISCOVERED THE VAPOR LEAK WHILE CONDUCTING A ROUTINE INSPECTION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AT THE RAIL YARD.  TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  DUPONT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED OF THE LEAK AT 1152 HOURS, 10/04/91, AND ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 1232 HOURS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT VAPOR WAS COMING FROM A THREE INCH LIQUID LINE DUE TO A DEFECTIVE BALL VALVE GASKET.  TEMPORARY REPAIR WAS MADE AND CAR WAS CLEARED TO MOVE BACK TO DUPONT'S BELLE, WV FACILITY WHERE THE CAR WAS TO BE OFF LOADED AND THE BALL VALVE REPLACED.  CAR WAS CLEARED BACK TO DUPONT AT 1310 HOURS, 10/04/19.

DRIVER WAS FILLING A 275 GALLON HOME HEATING OIL TANK.  THE VENT WAS NOT CLEAR SO THE DRIVER COULDN'T HEAR A GOOD VENT SOUND AND HE OVERFILLED TANK.  2 PINTS OF OIL LEAKED OUT.  TANK WAS SCHEDULED TO RECEIVE A VENT ALARM AND SPILL WAS CLEANED UP.
DRIVER STARTED TO FILL TANK, VENT WAS TRAPPED WITH PRODUCT, AS HE WAS FILLING TANK OIL RAN OUT OF VENT.  DRIVER CLEANED SPILL UP.  VENT WILL BE CHECKED TO MAKE SURE NO PROBLEM EXISTS.

WHILE DRIVER WAS MOVING TRUCK FROM ONE STOP TO NEXT THE HOSE UNROLLED ONTO ROAD.  END OF HOSE WAS DAMAGED AND ABOUT 3 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL LEAKED OUT.  DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE AIR BRAKE ON HOSE REEL.  HOSE REPLACED, VALVE CHECKED ON HOSE BRAKE.  NO PROBLEM FOUND.
AS DRIVER WAS FILLING TANK OIL LEAKED OUT OF A BAD VENT.  VENT TO BE REPLACED BEFORE OIL DELIVERIES TO BE RESUMED.
WHILE DRIVER WAS FILLING A TANK THE VENT PIPE HAD OIL IN IT FROM A PREVIOUS DELIVERY AND ABOUT 1 GALLON OF OIL LEAKED OUT.  PROBLEM SHOULD NOT OCCUR AGAIN.

DRIVER GAUGED TANK TO KNOW HOW MUCH OIL TO DELIVER.  HE LOOKED AT THE WRONG CHART AND TRIED TO DELIVER 200 GALLONS MORE THAN THE TANK WOULD HOLD. AFTER ABOUT 15 GALLONS CAME OUT OF THE TANK HE CLOSED THE NOZZLE AND STARTED TO CLEAN UP SPILL.  DRIVER WAS REMINDED OF CARE TO HE TAKEN IN GAUGING TANKS CORRECTLY.

WHILE DRIVER WAS FILLING TANK THE TANK WAS VENTING, BUT THE DRIVER REPORTED A WEAK VENT SOUND.  AS THE TANK FILLED ABOUT 1 QUART OF LIQUID SPRAYED OUT OF VENT PIPE.  OIL WAS CLEANED UP.  VENT TO BE REPAIRED.

INCIDENT HAPPENED AT TERMINAL LOCATION WHILE UNLOADING.  THERE WERE 2 SKIDS OF REELS ON REAR TO THIS TRLR 28 5467.  THE SKIDS WERE NOT THE NORMAL 4X$, BUT "SHORTER".  DRUMS WERE LOADED DIRECTLY BEHIND THE SKIDS, WITH NO DUNNAGE UNDERNEATH, NOR ANY DUNNAGE OR EMPTY PALLETS IN-BETWEEN. MANY CASES OF CHEWING TOBACCO HAD FALLEN OVER IN TRANSIT, COVERING UP THE DRUMS.  PERSON UNLOADING DID NOT KNOW THE DRUMS WERE BEHIND THE SKID, WHEN HE PLACED BLADES THRU THE PALLET TO UNLOAD, ONE OF THEM PUNCTURED THIS DRUM.  VERY BASIC PREVENTION METHODS, I.E. -- DUNNAGE UNDERNEATH, AND EMPTY PALLETS IN BETWEEN, WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS FROM OCCURING.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: A) WHAT CAUSED INCIDENT:  THE STATION HAD FOUR TANKS, (2) UNLEADED ONE NORTH THE OTHER SOUTH.  ONE EACH OF LEADED REGULAR AND PREMIUM NO-LEAD. THE REMOTES ARE POSITIONED TWO FEET TO THE RIGHT OF THE DRAWBAR WHEN THE TRUCK IS IN POSITION.  ALL PRODUCT IS DROPPED THROUGH THE REMOTES. DRIVER ARRIVED AT STATION AND BEGAN DROPPING UNLEADED IN THE SOUTH TANK, HOOKED UP THE LEADED REGULAR TO THE REMOTE AND BEGAN DROPPING 1-REG. BECAUSE OF PREVIOUS PROBLEMS WITH STATION EQUIPMENT, HE WATCHED THE 1-REG FOR ABOUT 20 SECONDS TO MAKE SURE THERE WERE NO PROBLEMS.  NONE WERE OBSERVED.  AFTER ABOUT 5 MINUTES OF DELIVERY, GAS WAS OBSERVED COMING FROM THE 1-REG FILL BOX ONTO THE DRIVEWAY.  DELIVERY WAS IMMEDIATELY STOPPED. PRODUCT CONTINUED TO COME OUT OF THE FILL BOX UNTIL THE HOSE CLEARED. AFTER THE SOUTH TANK, HE SWITCHED TO THE NORTH TANK AND ATTEMPTED DELIVERY.  PRODUCT IMMEDIATELY BEGAN TO FILL THE BOX AND DELIVERY WAS TERMINATED. B) ACTION TAKEN:  HE PICKED UP AND PUT AWAY ALL HOSES AND FITTINGS THEN USING ABSORBENT TOWEL, WIPED UP THE 1-REG.  NO UNLEADED CAME OUT OF THE FILL BOX.  THE DRIVER CALLED THE SHELL DISPATCH CENTER INFORMED THEM THAT THE STAION EQUIPMENT WAS UNSAFE FOR FURTHER DELIVERIES AND DRIVER WOULD NOT BE ABLE TO COMPLETE THE DELIVERY FOR SAFETY REASONS. C&D) ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE PROBLEMS:  SHELL OIL COMPANY REDLINED STATION UNTIL REPAIRS WERE MADE TO TANKS AND STATION EQUIPMENT.  AND DRIVER WILL CONTINUE TO PROCEED WITH CAUTION WHEN UNLOADING AT THIS STATION AS WELL AS ALL DELIVERIES.  (NOTE:  CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT PAD HANDLED BY STATION MANAGER). E) ATTACHED PAPERWORK:  SHIPPING DOCUMENTS & EMPLOYEE'S WRITTEN STATEMENT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: A) WHAT CAUSED INCIDENT:  WHILE OUR DRIVER WAS LOADING OUR TRUCK & TRAILER WITH HIS LOAD OF 4000 GALLONS OF SUPER UNLEADED, 3000 GALLONS OF REGULAR UNLEADED AND 1800 GALLONS OF REGULAR LEADED, HE BEGAN DOING HIS NECESSARY PAPERWORK, AT WHICH TIME HE HEARD GAS COMING OUT OF THE TRAILER.  HE THEN TOOK IMMEDIATE ACTION TO STOP THE FLOW OF GASOLINE, UPON STOPPING THE FLOW PRODUCT, HE BEGAN CLEANING UP THE GASOLINE (WITH ABSORBENT PADS) THAT HAD SPILLED OUT OF THE CONTAINMENT AREA ONTO THE BLACKTOP.  AFTER CLEANING UP THE SPILL, WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF A SHELL DRIVER, TO THE BEST OF THEIR ABILITY.  OUR DRIVER PROCEEDED TO DELIVER THE LOAD OF FUEL AS SCHEDULED. B) ACTION TAKEN:  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP THE GASOLINE WITH ABSORBENT PADS, (WHICH WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT A LATER DATE BY OUR OUTSIDE ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY). C) ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE PROBLEMS:  IT IS THE POLICY OF THIS COMPANY TO ALWAYS CONTACT THE DISPATCHER ON DUTY OF ANY SPILL NO MATTER WHAT THE SIZE, THIS POLICY IS KNOWN BY ALL EMPLOYEES, THEREFORE WE WERE NOT TOLD OF THE INCIDENT UNTIL THE FOLLOWING MORNING, BY OUR CUSTOMER, SHELL OIL, WHICH CAUSED DEFAMATION OF COMPANIES CHARACTER.  IN ADDITION, WE FELT THAT IT WAS NECESSARY TO TERMINATE THE EMPLOYEE WHO CAUSED THIS INCIDENT.  AND THERE WAS A DRIVERS MEETING THAT DELT WITH THE IMPORTANCE OF ALL DRIVERS TO CALL THE DISPATCHER ON DUTY OF ANY INCIDENT THAT CAUSES DAMAGE OF SORT. D) ATTACHED PAPERWORK: DRIVERS STATEMENT & SHIPPING PAPERS.

column168: FRV RECEIVED LOADED CAR FROM CNW ON JUNE 29, 1991.  CAR ARRIVED IN APPLETON ON JUNE 29, 1991.  CAR STOPPED AT REPAP ON JULY 22, 1991. INCIDENT OCCURRED ON OCTOBER 2, 1991. CAR WAS STORED IN FENCED AREA.  CHLORING WAS BEING PIPED INTO BUILDING ON AN AS-NEEDED BASIS.  INVESTIGATION RESULTS INDICATED NO DEFECTS IN THE TANK CAR.  FOUND LEAK IN THE PIPE FITTING. DAN PHELAN, RAW MATERIAL COORDINATOR, AT REPAP INDICATED MOISTURE GOT INSIDE A PIPE FITTING ATTCHED TO THE UNLOADING PIPE.  THE CHLORINE/MOISTURE INTERATION CAUSED SOME CORROSION AROUND THE PIPE FITTING, CONSEQUENTLY CAUSING LEAK.

INDICATION OF POSSIBLE LEAK REPORTED BY CAR INSPECTOR. INSPECTION INDICATED GASKET MISSING AT DOME LID. CAR SET OUT OF  TRAIN AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED OF DEFECT THROUGH CHEMTREC. SHIPPER MAD REPAIRS NAD CAR CONTINUED IN SERVICE TO DESTINATION.

ODOR COMING FROM LIQUID VALVE.  DEFECTIVE VALVE WOULD LET ODOR PASS THROUGH VALVE IN CLOSED POSITION.  MADE A RUBBER GASKET AND INSTALLED BETWEEN COVER PLATE AND VALVE. CAR WAS STENCILLED T-BUTYL MERCAPLAN PLACARDS 2347 FLAMMABLE 3 RESIDUE. WAYBILL SHOWS DIETHYL KETONE, PLACARDS SHOULD BE 1156.
HOSE RUPTURED DURING UNLOADING.  400 GAL WAS SPILLED ON GROUND CLEANUP WAS DONE BY CARSILL. HOSE HAD BEEN PRESSURE CHECKED 2 WEEKS PRIOR RO INCIDENT. WITH NO DEFECTS FOUND.

ON OCTOBER 3, 1991 BIRMINGHAM SOUTHERN CREW WAS MAKING A COUPLING IN TRACK #14.  AS TANK CAR #NATX 076878 LOADED WIHT COAL TAR DISTILLATES COUPLED, THE CONTENTS OF TANK SLOSHED OUT OF TOP OF TANK CAR.  DOME COVER WAS LOOSE AND HAD NOT BEEN SECURED.  TANK CAR WAS REPAIRED ON BIRMINGHAM SOUTHERN PROPERTY BY ALLIED CHEMICAL REPAIRMAN.  ATTACHED IS A COPY OF ASSISTANT TRAINMASTER J.D. SILINSKY'S REPORT ON THIS ANCIDENT.

OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING A LOAD OF NO. 2 DIESEL FUEL TO PENSKE TRUCK LEASING AT 415 11TH AVE. IN NASHVILLE, TN.  APPARENTLY THERE IS A PROBLEM WITH THE OVERFILL PROTECTOR IN THE FILL PIPE AT THIS LOCATION, BUT OUR DRIVER WAS NOT AWARE OF THIS PROBLEM.  THE OVER FILL PROTECTOR DEVICE SNAPPED SHUT CAUSING A PRESSURE BUILD-UP WHICH BLEW OUT THE TIGHT-FILL HOSE CONNECTOR AND BEFORE THE DRIVER COULD SHUT DOWN THE FLOW OF FUEL, APPROX. 100 TO 200 GALLONS SPILLED.  CALLS WERE MADE TO THE NASHVILLE FIRE DEPT. (CAPT. COFFEY - NFD).  FERGUSON-HARBOR SERVICE DID THE CLEAN-UP AND THEIR EST. OF ONLY 50 TO 100 GALLONS AT MOST.  CONTACTED NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (MR. JAMISON) NRC REPORT #91836, ALSO MR. JAMES FRANCIS OF TEMA WAS CONTACTED.  THE SPILL WAS TOTALLY CONTAINED ON PENSKE YARD AND NO CONTAMINATION RESULTED FROM SPILL. WOOTEN PERSONNEL ON THE SCENE WAS MR. JERRY LATHUM - TERM. MGR., MR. H.B. BRYANS - SUPERVISOR AND ONE SHOP MAN.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: 10-04-91 11:00 AM DRIVER CLINTON HARDY WAS TAKING PACKAGE OUT OF REAR DOOR OF HIS PACKAGE CAR AND IT FELL TO THE GROUND.  IMMEDIATELY HE NOTICED A SMELL AND SAW LEAKAGE.  RUTGERS BIO AG ENGINEERING DEPT. SECURITY RUTH TOLD CLINTON NOT TO PICK UP THE PACKAGE.  SHE CALLED RUTGERS ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH AND SAFETY DEPT.  ROSE HADDAD AND WENDY GROSSMAN ARRIVED TO BEGIN THE CLEAN UP.  CLINTON HARDY LEFT AND SAID HE WOULD RETURN THAT NIGHT. CLINTON WAS TOLD THERE WAS NO WAY THE PACKAGE CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BECAUSE IT WAS NOT MARKED AS SUCH.  ENVIRONNEMTAL SERVICE WAS CALLED TO COORDINATE THE CLEAN UP.  THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SS GALLON DRUM AND THE DIRT THAT WAS CONTAMINATED WAS PLACED ON TOP OF THE PACKAGE IN THE DRUM.  WHEN RUTGERS CALLED UPS, MIKE D'AMICO TOLD RUTGERS THAT WE WOULD NEED TO CHECK THE PACKAGE, SO THEY TRANSFERRED THE CONTENTS INTO ANOTHER SS GALLON DRUM.  ACCORDING TO MARTIN COSTELLO, WENDY GROSSMAN AND ROSE HADDAD OF RUTGERS ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH AND SAFETY THE DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED AS AN ORM A NOS (DIMETHYL-FORMAMIDE) AND DID NOT HAVE THE PROTECTIVE INNER PACKAGING.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0915, KENNETH BURNETT (TERRA FIRST DRIVER) CALLED REPORTING A LEAK ON HIS TRAILER BOUND TO ENSCO AT EL DORADO, AR.  THE DRIVER CONTAINED THE LEAK WITH ABSORBANT AND PLASTIC UNTIL A CREW FROM LAIDLAW ARRIVED.  THE CLEAN UP CREW FOUND 1 DRUM TO HAVE A PIN-HOLE IN THE TOP QUARTER OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE LOAD WAS OFF LOADED ONTO A LAIDLAW TRUCK.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WHICH COVERED AN AREA OF APPROXIMATELY 1 SQUARE YARD.  1 INCH OF GRAVEL, 2-5" OF DIRT AND ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO 4 DRUMS.  THE ENTIRE OPERATION TOOK APPROXIMATELY 6 HOURS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGING FAILURE OF ANY KIND ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT. THIS WAS A BULK DELIVERY OF DIESEL FUEL TO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK. UPON ARRIVAL TO THE FACILITY, OUR DRIVER CONTACTED THE AREA FOREMAN WHO UNLOCKED THE TANK AND CONFIRMED THAT THE TANK WOULD HOLD OUR FULL LOAD THE 7500 GALLONS.  WHAT THE FOREMAN DID NOT DO WAS INDICATE TO OUR DRIVER THAT THE STORAGE TANK WAS BAFFLED INTERNALLY AND THAT ONE HALF OF THE TANK WOULD FILL BEFORE THE OTHER.  AS OUR DRIVER NEARED COMPLETION OF HIS DELIVERY THE BACK HALF OF THE TANK OVERFILLED CAUSING FUEL TO SPRAY OUT OF THE VENT PIPE ONTO THE TANK.  AS OUR DRIVER WAS AT THE CONTROLS OF THE PUMP, ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT OF FUEL CAME OUT.  ABOUT 4 WHEEL BARROW LOADS OF CONTAMINATED SAND WAS REMOVED FROM UNDER THE TANK.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED A REFERENCE NUMBER OF 9107628 TO THIS INCIDENT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: OCT 8 1991 ABOUT 8:00 O'CLOCK CENTRAL TIME TO STOPPED AT A SHELL STATION TO CHECK MY TIRES AND TO PHONE IN WHEN I CHECKED TIRE; NOTICE A GREAT DEAL OF FLUID LEAKING OUT THE RIGHT HAND CORNER AND ABOUT 5 FOOT OF RIGHT SIDE CORNER LEAKING. 1ST I PUT A SHEET OF PLASTIC LINER TO CONTAIN AND PREVENT ANY MORE GROUND CONTAMINATION THEN I CALLED TERRA.  FIRST GAVE A LIST OF WHAT WAS IN THE DRUMS THEN PURCHASED 150 LBS OF DRY SWEEP IN AN ATTEMPT TO STOP AND FUTURE CONTAIN THE LEAK.  WHEN I OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR FUMES FROM LEAKING DRUM WITH SMOKE.  THEN I CALLED COMPANY AND CALLED GSX. LAIDLAW TALKED WITH THOMAS YOUNG & BRUCE MARGAN THEY DISPATCHED 1 TRUCK 1 HAZMAT TEAM TO MY LOCATION. THEY ALSO NOTIFIED STATE HIGHWAY, LOCAL POLICE & EPA, OES. BEFORE THEY GOT THERE DAWN ALL SAFETY EQUIPMENT GOT UP IN TRAILER TO TRY TO COUNT LEAKING DRUM (WAS UNABLE TO TELL HOW MANY BUT ESTIMATED SEVERAL DRUMS) EVERY HOUR CHECK TO SEE IF STILL LEAKING UNTIL GSX CAME.  GSX GOT THERE AT 6:00 - OVER PACKED 5 DRUMS AND 3 DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL SPILL TOTALLY CLEANED UP.  OWNER OF SHELL WANTED GRAVEL REPLACED.  WE WORKED OUT AN AGREEMENT WHERE ONE OF THE LOCAL DEPUTY WOULD REPLACED GRAVEL FOR 25.00. ALL OK WHEN I LEFT OES STATE HIGYWAY & LOCAL REPS WERE HAPPY. (SIGNED BY KEVIN R. BURNETT - DRIVER). RE: SECTION IV, ITEM 12:  PER MR. HOLLIS - PRODUCT SPILLED - WASTE ORM-A, NOS ITEM "I" FOUND ON PAGE 2 OF MANIFEST.  NB:  LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL ALSO FILED A REPORT WITH DOT 12/05/91.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ACCOUNT OF SPILL - DRIVER INDICATED HE HAD TWO COMPARTMENTS OF GASOHOL LOADED WITH 2,300 GALLONS AND 1,050 GALONS RESPECTIVELY.  HE INDICATED HE HAD STUCK THE MIDDLE TANK AND IT READ 55" BEFORE HE BAGAN TO UNLOAD.  HE FAILED TO USE THE "LOCK-TIGHT" NOZZLE BECAUSE HE COULD NOT GET IT TO FIT ON THE TANK OPENING SO HE USED AN OLDER STYLE NOZZLE WHICH FITS INSIDE THE TANK OPENING AND WELLS, WHEN LOCKED DOWN, TO MAKE THE SEAL. HE INDICATED HE HAD UNLOADED THE 2,300 GALLON COMPARTMENT AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING THE 1,050 GALLON COMPARTMENT WHEN A VEHICLE PULLED UP AND PARKED CLOSE TO THE TRANSPORT ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE FROM THE TRAILER VALVES AND TANK OPENINGS.  HE WENT TO THE OTHER SIDE OF THE TRANSPORT TO ASK THE DRIVER NOT TO PARK THAT CLOSE WHILE HE WAS UNLOADING.  HE WENT TO THE CAB OF THE TRUCK AND ESTIMATED HE WAS OUT OF SIGHT OF THE TANK OPENINGS FOR ONLY A COUPLE OF MINUTES.  HE INDICATED THAT SOMEONE TOLD HIM HE HAD GAS FLOWING ONTO THE DRIVE.  HE RUSHED TO THE OTHER SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND SAID HE SHUT DOWN THE TRAILER VALVE JUST AS THE SPILL REACHED AND GUTTER ON THE EAST SIDE OF WEST STREET. HE INDICATED THAT SHUTTING OFF THE TRAILER DID NOT IMMEDIATELY STOP THE PRODUCT FROM SPILLING OUT OF THE TANK OPENING AROUND THE NOZZLE.  THE SPILL WENT WEST ON THE DRIVE TO THE STREET GUTTER THEN SOUTH TO THE CORNER AND DUMPED INTO THE STORM SEWER.  THE DRIVER STUCK THE MIDDLE TANK (THAT SPILLED) BEFORE HE BEGAN UNLOADING AND GOT A 55" READING.  AFTER THE TANK HAD SETTLED AND STOPPED OVERFLOWING THE READING WAS 93". WHEN THE SPILL WAS ORIGINALLY INVESTIGATED IT WAS THOUGHT THAT THE CUSTOMER ORDERED MORE THAN HE COULD HOLD.  IT WAS LATER FOUND OUT THAT THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN THE WRONG INFORMATION BY THE STATION ATTENDANT WHEN HE ASKED HER WHICH PRODUCT WENT IN WHICH TANK.  THE CENTER TANK WHICH OVERFLOWED WAS MARKED FOR MORE THAN ON PRODUCT AND THE EAST TANK WHICH WOULD HAVE TAKEN THE DELIVERY WAS MARKED NL+ WHICH COULD MEAN NOLEAD PLUS PREMIUM OR NOLEAD PLUS ALCOHOL.  THE MARKING CONFUSION IS WHAT PROMPTED THE DRIVER TO ASK THE ATTENDANT BEFORE HE STARTED TO UNLOAD.

column168: WHILE STOPPING AT LORI'S RESTAURANT IN CALDWELL, OHIO, THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE INVOLVED, BRUCE COLLINS, NOTICED A LIQ DRIPPING FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR ONTO A MUD FLAP. HE OPENED THE TRAILER DOORS AND FOUND THAT THE TOTE CONSIGNED TO ELKEM METALS WAS LEAKING. HE THEN PULLED THE VEHICLE AWAY FROM THE RESTAURANT AND INTO A LARGE GRAVEL LOT AND CALLED THE TERMINAL. WE ADVISED THE DRIVER TO FOLLOW THE PROCEDURE OF GUIDE 60 OF THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK. WE IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE EMERGENCY CONTACT NUMBER LISTED OF THE SHIPPING ORDER AND GAVE THEM ALL OF THE DETAILS. THE ADVISED THEY WOULD CALL US BACK. WE WERE THEN CONTACTED BY THE SHIPPER WHO CONTACTED THE E.P.A. AND CHEM SERVICE, A HAZARDOUS MATS TEAM IN COLUMBUS, OHIO. WHEN THE DRIVER CALLED BACK, HE ADVISED THAT TWO OF OUR SALARIED EMPLOYEES HAD ARRIVED. THEY HAD LOCATED A LEAKING VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TOTE AND HAD SECURED A PLASTIC BAG AROUND THIS VALVE. THIS STOPPED THE LEAKAGE. THEY ALSO APPLIED AN OIL-DRY MATERIAL TO THE LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. CHEM-SERVICE ARRIVED IN CALDWELL AT 3:15PM AND PUMPED THE CORROSIVE LIQUID INTO 7 DRUMS. THEY COMPLETED THE JOB AT 5:15PM. OUR DRIVER WAITED FROM 8:50AM UNTIL THEY FINISHED. OUR TWO SALARIED PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT 10:30PM AND STAYED UNTIL APPROXIMATELY 3:30PM.

column168: ON 10/06/91, A UPRR SWITCHMAN WAS SPRAYED WITH ACID FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR ACFX 88983.  THE SWITCHMAN RECEIVED FIRST AID TREATMENT FOR AN ACID BURN TO HIS EAR AT A LOCAL HOSPITAL AND RETURNED TO WORK.  THE TANK CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED AT THE ALEXANDRIA YARD. THE NEXT MORNING NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) TOM ROBINSON, THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, CHEMTREC AND ASARCO, THE SHIPPER. TROOPER FRED FONTENOT OF THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE FOUND THE CAR TO BE LEAKING FROM A DEFECTIVE WELD ON THE EDUCTION PIPE FLANGE.  HE WAS ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK BY OPENING THE QUICK FILL PORT, THUS RELIEVING THE PRESSURE THAT WAS FORCING PRODUCT UP THE EDUCTION PIPE.  AN ESTIMATED 50 TO 60 GALLONS OF ACID THAT HAD SPILLED ON THE GROUND IN THE SWITCHYARD, WAS NEUTRALIZED ON SITE.  THE DEFECTIVE WELD ON THE EDUCTION FLANGE WAS REPAIRED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT. *THERE WAS NO ATTACHED SHEET AS NOTED ON REPORT*

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) TOM SMITH WAS NOTIFIED THAT TWO RESIDUE INTERMODAL TANKS (ICLU 942224 & ICLU 946245) HAD STRONG ODOR EMITTING FROM THE TANKS.  SSA/HM SMITH RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT TO FACILITATE OFF LOADING, THE VESSELS WERE CHARGED WITH AN INERT GAS.  IT APPEARED THAT DURING THIS PROCESS THE PRODUCT EXIT LINE WAS CLOSED BEFORE THE COMPRESSED GAS LINE WAS CLOSED CAUSING THE TANK TO BE LEFT WITH A CHARGE.  THE ATTACHED PRESSURE GAUGES INDICATED THE TANKS HAD BETWEEN 35 AND 52 POUNDS OF PRESSURE.  HIGH AMBIENT TEMPERATURE, LOW 90'S, CAUSED THE ODOR OF THE RESIDUE PRODUCT TO SEEP PAST THE MANWAY GASKET. SSA/HM SMITH CONTACTED PAUL STEDMAN OF ATOCHEM WHO DISPATCHED RESPONSE TEAM.  SSA/HM TIGHTENED MANWAY LOCKING LUGS AND MOVED RAILCAR TO SHADED AREA TO ABATE PROBLEM UNTIL RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED. UPON ARRIVAL OF ATOCHEM RESPONSE TEAM, THE TANKS WERE VENTED AND SEALED. ODOR EMISSIONS STOPPED.

INSPECTOR MATY'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE "ZOOK" 100 PSI FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT HAD BURST.  INSPECTOR MATY REPLACED FRANGIBLE WITH AN "OSECO" 100 PSI DISC AND CAR WAS WASHED WITH A SOLUTION OF SODIUM BICARBONATE.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT. MR JOE MILLAZO AT CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

YARD PERSONNEL AT THE ALEXANDRIA, LA, YARD REPORTED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA AND SMALL VAPOR LEAK COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 40692. SSA/HM ROBINSON AND SA/HM WOMACK RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A LEAK IN THE B-END LIQUID VALVE. CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT. CHEMTREC, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND FARMLAND INDUSTRIES WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: ON 10/21/91, TWO EMPLOYEES. JACK CULLLEY AND CRAIG RUNNELS, DETECTED ODORS COMING FROM CAR PLMX 280009.  AL PARROTT, MANAGER MECHANICAL MAITENANCE EXAMINED THE CAR. MANAGER PARROTT TESTED THE AREA USING A GAS-TRAC AND FOUND NO FLAMMABLE VAPORS.  THE AREA WAS WASHED DOWN WITH WATER AND CAR MOVED TO AN ISOLATED AREA.  SENOIR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) GEOFF REEDER HAD BEEN CONTACTED AND UPON HIS ARRIVAL THE CAR WAS INSPECTED.  SSA/HM INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE MECHANISM HAD BEEN SHEARED AWAY IN A DERAILMENT OVER THE WEEKEND.  THE VALVE PLATE AND SEAL WERE IN TACT. ALL OTHER VALVES AND FITTING WERE CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  SSA/HM REEDER PERFORMED A PRESSURE TEST AND NO PRESSURE WAS ON THE CAR. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR CAR TO BE LOADED ON A FLAT CAR FOR TRANSPORT TO SHOP FOR REPAIR.

SSA/HM LOE RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT LIQUID WAS COMING FROM THE DRAIN, LEFT SIDE COMPARTMENT. SSA/HM LOW REMOVED SEAL KCS-N-14215 AND NOTED LEAK COMING FROM LIQUID VALVE NUMBER 102. MCCALLISTER OF UNION CARBIDE CORPORATION WERE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

ON 10/15/91, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) DON LOW WAS NOTIFIED BY BOB STINE, MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, THAT TANK CAR GATX 69248, PHOSPHORIC ACID, WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM AREA.  THE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED IN YERMO YARDS, YERMO, CA, MP CX650/TRACK RD 203.  MANAGER STINE ALSO ADVISED THAT IT CORP., WILLINGTON, CA WAS EN ROUTE AND THE YERMO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON HAND.  SSA/HM LOW RESPONDED ANS IT CORPORATION WAS ON THE SCENE.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT G.W. NORMAN, MTO, HAD BUILT A DIKE TO CONTAIN THE ACID.  INSPECTION OF GATX 69248, JACKETED CAR, DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM UNDER STEEL SADDLE (SKID PLATE), "B" END, LEAKING ONTO SAFETY CHAIN ATTACHED TO THE BLANK FLANGE, BOTTOM OUTLEY VAVLE.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING AT APPROXMATELY TWO TO FIVE GALLONS PER MINUTE.  HARD PLASTIC POOL WAS PLACED UNDER CAR TO CONTAIN PRODUCT AND PRODUCT WAS PUMPED FROM POOL INTO TWO PACIFIC ENVIRONMENTAL TANK TRUCKS.  THE LIQUID WAS VACUUMED FROM THE GROUND AREA. CHEMTREC, STATE AND COUNTY WERE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.  MR, NORM SELF, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS AND SIMPLOT COMPANY WERE ON THE SCENE. INSPECTION FROM THE MANWAY OF THE INTERIOR OF THE CAR DETERMINED APPROXIMATELY TWO FEET RIGHT OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS A ONE FOOT SCUFF AND THREE SMALLER ONE INCH SCUFFS NOTED ON THE LINER.  CAR WAS MADE B/O AND RETURNED TO SIMPLOT, POCATELLO, IDAHO.

DRIVER, ROBERT BRUSH, ARRIVED AT TIFFANY'S PETROLEUM AT 21:30 OCTOBER 10, 1991 TO UNLOAD 7500 GALLONS OF #2 FUEL OIL NA 1993.  IN PREPARATION FOR UNLOADING THE TANKER TRUCK MR. BRUSH CONNECTED THE PUMP OFF HOSE FROM TANKER TO PRODUCT LINE WHICH WAS A GASOLINE PIPE.  DRIVER CONNECTED THE HOSE TO THE WRONG PIPE AND PUMPED THE 7500 GALLONS OF #2 FUEL OIL INTO 5000 GALLON PLUS TANK SPILLING 4500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND.  DUE TO POOR LIGHTING UN UNLOADING AREA DRIVER MADE HOOK UP TO PIPE LINE COLORED BLUE WHICH WAS MID-GRADE GASOLINE TANK CAPACITY 5000 GALLONS. DRIVER SHOULD HAVE MADE HOOK UP TO GREEN LINE #2 FUEL OIL.  THERE ARE FIVE PIPE LINES COLORED CODED FOR UNLOADING PRODUCT.  NOTE: SEE PICTURE BLUE LINE LOOKED LIKE GREEN IN THE POORLY LIGHTED AREA.  CONTRIBUTION FACTORS TO SPILL:  1. POOR LIGHTING. 2. STORAGE TANKS (ABOVE GROUND) 100 FEET + FROM UNLOADING AREA.  3. STORAGE TANKS (50 FEET + ON A HILL ABOVE UNLOADING AREA - WITH AN EARTH CONTAINMENT WALL AROUND TANKS.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ALKALI, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ON 10/09/91, AT APPROXIMATELY 02:04, SORT SUPERVISOR PHIL SPAHR REPORTED A SPILL IN THE REPACK AREA OF BUILDING "C" DOOR C-6 AT OUR SORT FACILITY. THE SPILL WAS REPORTED AS A CLEAR LIQUID, NO ODOR, 2 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT. CERT 7 HAZ-MAT COORDINATOR KAREN NICHOLS AND CERT 12 P/T HAZMAT SPECIALIST RHONDA CLONCH, ARRIVED ON THE SCENE APPROXIMATELY 02:06.  THEY FOUND A WET CELL BATTERY LEAKING ONTO THE FLOOR.  THE SUPERVISOR ADVISED KAREN THAT THE 2 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WERE IN THE RESTROOM WASHING THEIR HANDS, AND CFR HAD ALREADY BEEN CALLED TO RESPOND.  CERT 7 AND CERT 12 LOCATED THE AIRWAYBILL FROM A P/T SORTER WORKING THE AREA.  CERT 7 AND CERT 12 PH'D THE TOP OF THE BATTERY, RECEIVED A READING OF 13, A STRONG CAUSTIC. THE BATTERY LEAKED DUE TO A CRACKED AREA AROUND ONE OF THE CONNECTING TERMINALS, AND ONE CORNER OF THE BATTERY WAS ALSO CRACKED. AT APPROXIMATELY 02:07, CERT 11 HAZMAT COORDINTOR AND CERT 10 ADDIE CAMPTON WERE ENROUTE TO C-6 TO ASSIST.  CERT 7 ADVISED CERT 11 TO BRING THE SPILL-X WITH HER TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL.  CERT 7 DID A QUICK CHECK FOR ANY SPECIAL MARKINGS OR LABELS AND FOUND NONE.  THERE WAS ALSO NO INNER ABSORBENT OR PACKING MATERIAL INSIDE THE BOX. 02:08 - CERT 11 AND CERT 10 ARRIVED ON SCENE AND CERT 7 AND CERT 12 WERE CALLED AWAY TO A PRIORITY 2 SPILL.  CERT 11 AND CERT 10 REMAINED ON SCENE TO FINISH THE NEUTRALIZATION AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  CERT 10 WAS INSTRUCTED TO PH THE LIQUID.  FOUND THE SAME READING AS CERT 7.  CERT 10 WAS THEN ADVISED TO PUT ON A CHEMICAL SUIT, GLOVES AND FACE SHIELD.  SHE PLACED THE BATTERY PACK INTO IT'S BOX, THEN INTO A PLASTIC BAG TO BE TRANSPORTED TO THE HAZMAT AREA.  THE LIQUID ON THE FLOOR WAS NEUTRALIZED. THE EMPLOYEES WERE TALKED TO ABOUT WHAT THEY WERE IN CONTACT WITH.  CERT 11 AND CERT 10 CLEARED THE SCENE AT 02:31.  CFR DID AN ACCIDENT REPORT ON THE TWO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT. WHEN THE BATTERY WAS FURTHER INSPECTED, IT WAS FOUND TO BE A DOT 128 FIBERBOARD BOX, MANUFACTURED BY THE STONE CONTAINER CORP. IN WESTFIELD, MA 01085.  THE REST OF THE MANUFACTURER'S SEAL WAS ILLEGIBLE DUE TO WEAR OF THE BOX.  THR BOX SIZE WAS APPROXIMATELY 17" X 7 6" X 7".  THERE WAS ALSO AN ADDRESS LABEL ATTACHED TO THE BOX.  IT IS ENCLOSED WITH THIS STATEMENT. INSIDE THE BOX WAS A BLUE METAL CASING FOR THE BATTERY, MEASURING APPROXIMATELY 16 1/2 X 6 1/2 X 5 X 6 1/2 INCHES.  ONE END WAS EQUIPPED WITH A LIP FOR SECURING THE CASE INTO THE BATTERY.  ONE END OF THIS CASE WAS A STICKER.  IT READ FOR PARTS AND SERVICE CALL 1-(813)-398-6559 OR 1-(800)-543-8311 .  CURRENT DEVICES, INC. 10946 70TH AVENUE, NORTH SEMINOLE, FL  34642.  MEDICAL BATTERY (SAME PHONE NUMBERS AS PREVIOUSLY LISTED).  MODEL 30-12H120, SERIAL #090391A, DATE 9/31/91, CDI LOANER,  ONE SIDE OF THE CASE WAS WRITTEN ON IT: BATTERY STORAGE - CALMIUM BATTERY O.C.V. FULL CHARGE 117.0 VOLTS, - CHARGING METHODS - CONSTANT CURRENT 1.3 AMPS FOR 16 HOURS, CONSTANT POTENTIAL - 135.0 VOLTS FOR 4 HOURS, G.E. CATALOG NUMBER 43B011TB06 CONSISTS OF THE THREE 43B01

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THIS LETTER IS IN RESPONSE TO YOUR INQUIRY OF INCIDENT #912811. ON THE EVENING OF OCTOBER 2, 1991 AN AMOCO DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO AN AMOCO SERVICE STATION LOCATED AT 1395 BUTTERFIELD ROAD, AURORA, IL., WHEN A CUSTOMER ACCIDENTLY RAN OVER THE PRODUCT DELIVERY HOSE CAUSING A BREAK AND A PRODUCT SPILL OF UNKNOWN QUANTITY.  (WE ESTIMATE MAXIMUM QUANTITY AT 50 GALLONS).  IT WAS RAINING VERY HARD AT THE TIME OF THIS INCIDENT. AURORA POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  BECAUSE OF THE HEAVY RAIN THE PRODUCT RAPIDLY DISSIPATED MAKING ANY RECOVERY ATTEMPTS IMPOSSIBLE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TREATED THE AREA WITH CHEMICALS AND ALSO FURTHER HOSED IT DOWN.  NO OTHER ACTION WAS TAKEN AS EMERGENCY CONDITIONS NO LONGER EXISTED AND PRODUCT RECOVERY WAS IMPOSSIBLE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON DATE AND TIME LISTED ON REPORT, I SGT. DANNY PURVIS, WAS DISPATCHED TO AN ACCIDENT ON HIGHWAY 87 INVOLVING A GAS TRUCK AND ANOTHER VEHICLE.  UPON MY ARRIVAL, I OBSERVED AN INDUSTRIAL WELDING AND TOOL SUPPLIES TRUCK AND A TOYOTA 4 WHEEL DRIVE PICK UP.  BOTH VEHICLES WERE LAYING ON THEIR SIDES, WITH THE LIQUID NITROGEN TRUCK LAYING ON THE DRIVERS SIDE WITH DAMAGE TO THE PASSENGER SIDE, AND THE TOYOTA PICKUP LAYING ON THE PASSENGER SIDE WITH DAMAGE TO THE DRIVERS SIDE.  THERE WAS A SPRAY OF NITROGEN FUMES COMING FROM THE TRUCK AND DIESEL FUEL WAS LEAKING FROM THE MOTOR COMPARTMNET.  THE MONROE COUNTY E.M.S. DIRECTOR, MS. KAY GAY AND HER EMPLOYEES ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND STOPPED ALL TRAFFIC AND EVACUATED THE IMMEDIATE AREA, DUE TO THE FACT THAT SHE THOUGHT THERE WAS A HAZARDOUS SITUATION INVOLVED. AFTER TALKING WITH THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #2, HE STATED THAT HE WAS HEADED NORTH ON HIGHWAY 87, TRAVELING AT APPROX. 40 M.P.H., WHEN A SMALL TRUCK CAME OUT INTO THE ROADWAY IN FRONT OF HIM.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #2 STATED THAT HE SWERVED TO AVOID THE VEHICLE, BUT DID HIT IT A GLANCING BLOW, AND CONTINUED ON AND TURNED OVER IN THE DITCH.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #2 SUSTAINED MINOR INJURIES TO HIS RIGHT HAND AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE MONROE COUNTY HOSPITAL, WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 STATED THAT HE WAS HEADING EAST ON TREY TERRACE, TRAVELING AT APPROX 25 M.P.H., AND WAS APPROACHING THE STOP SIGN AT THE INTERSECTION OF TREY TERRACE AND HIGHWAY 87.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 STATED THAT AS HE APPROACHED THE STOP SIGN AND APPLIED THE BRAKES, THAT THE PEDDLE WENT TO THE FLOOR, AND WHEN HE PUMPED HIS BRAKES, THAT THEY WOULD NOT PUMP UP.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 STATED THAT HE ATTEMPTED TO MAKE A SHARP TURN TO THE RIGHT, BUT THAT HIS VEHICLE WENT INTO THE OPPOSITE LANE AND HE COULD NOT GET THE VEHICLE TO MAKE A COMPLETE TURN INTO HIS LANE.  THE DRIVER OR VEHICLE #1 STATED THAT THE TWO VEHICLES HIT A GLANCING BLOW AND THAT HE OVERTURNED IN THE HIGHWAY.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 WAS NOT INJURED, BUT HE WAS CHARGED WITH FAILURE TO STOP AT A STOP SIGN, AND WAS ADVISED THAT IF HIS BRAKES ARE DISCOVERED TO BE DEFECTIVE, THAT HE CAN BE CHARGED WITH DEFECTIVE EQUIPMENT.  AFTER TALKING WITH SEVERAL SUBJECTS ON THE SCENE, I LOCATED A WITNESS THAT GAVE BASICALLY THE SAME INFORMATION THAT THE TWO DRIVERS HAD GIVE.  THE WITNESS WHICH IS LISTED ABOVE, STATED THAT HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE, BUT THAT HE DID NOT STRIKE EITHER ONE OF THE TRUCKS, BUT DID RUN DOWN AN ENBANKMENT.  THE WITNESS STATED THAT AT THIS TIME, THAT HE RAN FROM HIS VEHICLE BACK TO THE OVERTURNED TRUCKS TO CHECK FOR INJURIES AND ASSIST THE DRIVERS IN GETTING OUT OF THEIR VEHICLES.  THE WITNESS STATED THAT THE DRIVER OF THE TOYOTA PICKUP STATED TO HIM THAT HE WAS APPROACHING THE STOP SIGN AND WHEN HE ATTEMPTED TO STOP, THAT HIS BRAKES FAILED AND HE WENT OUT INTO HIGHWAY 87, AND ATTEMPTED TO KEEP HIS TRUCK IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANE TO AVOID ONCOMING TRAFFIC, BUT WAS UNABLE TO

column168: WHILE LOADING PRO 168032476, THE TIP OF A FORKLIFT BLADE LANCED THE SIDE BOTTOM OF THE MIDDLE PAIL (1 OF 14) ON THE SKID.  THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED AFTER THE SHIPMENT WAS LOADED AND THE TRAILER DOOR CLOSED, WHEN OUR DRIVER/SALESMAN NOTICED A SMALL PUDDLE UNDERNEATH THE TRAILERS.  THE SKID WAS PULLED OFF THE TRAILER, SECURED AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM IMMEDIATELY WITH A PLASTIC LINER,  THE 5-6 GALLONS THAT LEAKED OUT WERE COVERED WITH SODA ASH AND A SOLID FORMED THEREAFTER.  THE OTHER PAILS WERE SECURED ON A SEPARATE SKID.  CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER AND THE CCX SAFETY SUPERVISOR WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED.  CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES WERE GIVEN BY THE SHIPPER (LIZ GALESTY, ATOCHEM).  SHIPPER WILL PICK-UP SHIPMENT 10/02/91 AT CCX DOCK, COLUMBUS, IN.  THROUGH USE OF INCREASED TRAINING, FUTURE SHIPMENTS WILL BE HANDLED IN PROPER FASHION WITH CAUTION ON USE OF FORK BLADES.

column168: CHECKER SHAWN GRIFFIN LOADED PAIL ON TRAILER AND WHEN HE PULLED DOCK BOARD OUT, A PAIL FELL AND HIT A SHARP SIDE OF THE DOCK BOARD PUNCTURING A SMALL HOLE AT THE TOP OF THE PAIL.  ABOUT SIX OUNCES OF FLUID LEAKED AND QUICKLY EVAPORATED.  WE ARE HOLDING PAIL TO SECURE DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER.

column168: (SA/HM) FH LERCH WAS NOTIFIED BY JOHN ROLLINS, WEST HUMPMASTER, THAT TANK CAR NATX 81019 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT. SA/HM LERCH RESPONDED AND NOTED THE SIDES OF THE CAR WERE COVERED WITH PRODUCT AND PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. SA/HM LERCH'S INSPSECTION DETERMINED THAT THE EIGHT SWING BOLTS TO THE MANWAY COVER PLATE WERE LOOSE, THE AIR VALVE SAFETY PLUG WAS NOT SECURED INTO VALVE, THE LIQUID VALVE AND SAFETY PLUG WER LOOSE, AND THE SEAL PIN TO PROTECTIVE HOUSING NOT SECURED. SA/HM LERCH CORRECTED ALL EXCEPTIONS AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS SECURED WITH SEAL UPC-53070. GARY LYON, KOCH REFINERY WAS NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.
